ians]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Stockholm]]\n[[Category:Sommar (radio program) hosts]]\n[[Category:Swedish film directors]]\n[[Category:Swedish music video directors]]\n[[Category:Swedish heavy metal drummers]]\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eVideography", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jonas_%C3%85kerlund"}
{"title_page": "Brachycnemina", "text_new": "{{short description|Suborder of cnidarians}}\n{{Automatic taxobox\n| image = Zoanthus sp act\u00ednica.jpg\n| image_caption = ''[[Zoanthus]]'' colony\n| taxon = Brachycnemina\n| authority = Haddon & Shackleton, 1891\n| subdivision_ranks = Families\n| subdivision = * [[Neozoanthidae]] <small>Herberts, 1972</small><br/>\n* [[Sphenopidae]] <small>Hertwig, 1882</small>\n* [[Zoanthidae]] <small>Rafinesque, 1815</small>\n}}\n\n'''Brachycnemina''' is a [[suborder]] of zoanthids in the order [[Zoantharia]].<ref name=\"SinnigerMontoya-Burgos2005\" /> Genetic analysis has been used to suggest Brachycnemina is a [[monophyletic]] group [[Genetic divergence|diverging]] within the [[paraphyletic]] [[Macrocnemina]].<ref name=\"SinnigerMontoya-Burgos2005\">{{cite journal|last1=Sinniger|first1=F.|last2=Montoya-Burgos|first2=J. I.|last3=Chevaldonn\u00e9|first3=P.|last4=Pawlowski|first4=J.|title=Phylogeny of the order Zoantharia (Anthozoa, Hexacorallia) based on the mitochondrial ribosomal genes|journal=Marine Biology|volume=147|issue=5|year=2005|pages=1121\u20131128|issn=0025-3162|doi=10.1007/s00227-005-0016-3|url=http://doc.rero.ch/record/315399/files/227_2005_Article_16.pdf}}</ref>\n\n==Characteristics==\nBrachycnemia species habitate most environments, ranging from shallow tropical [[reef]]s to [[cold seep]]s in the deep sea. It forms large colonies on [[intertidal]] and shallow [[Fringing reef|reef crest]]s.<ref name=\"Gujarat\" /> Due to the members of this suborder being loosely collected, there are no standard characteristics uniting them besides slight [[Morphology (biology)|morphological]], [[ecology|ecological]] and [[phylogenetic]] differences.<ref name=\"REIMER2010\">{{cite journal|last1=REIMER|first1=James Davis|title=Key to field identification of shallow water brachycnemic zoanthids (Order Zoantharia: Suborder Brachycnemina) present in Okinawa|journal=Galaxea, Journal of Coral Reef Studies|volume=12|issue=1|year=2010|pages=23\u201329|issn=1883-3969|doi=10.3755/galaxea.12.23}}</ref>\n\n==Subdivisions==\nThis suborder counts with 3 taxonomic families, namely [[Neozoanthidae]], which is [[monogeneric]]; [[Sphenopidae]], which includes sand-encrusted and colonial specimens like the commonly found ''[[Palythoa]]'' and ''[[Sphenopus]]'', itself found in a few discrete areas; and [[Zoanthidae]], whose belonging species do not show sand encrustation.<ref name=\"Gujarat\" /> A total of 6 known genera and over 163 species are comprised within the Brachycnemina.<ref name=GBIF.org>{{cite web|title=Brachycnemina Haddon & Shackleton, 1891|url=https://www.gbif.org/species/109752249|website=GBIF.org|publisher=GBIF.org|accessdate=21 May 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> ''Palythoa'' and ''Zoanthus'' are two of the most common coral genera and are intensively studied for their [[Bioactive compound|bioactive]] compounds.<ref name=\"Gujarat\">{{cite journal | last1 = Pandya Khushali | first1 = M. |display-authors=et al | year = 2014 | title = Occurrence of Zoanthid genus Isaurus from Saurashtra coast, Gujarat, India | url = | journal = European Journal of Zoological Research | volume = 3 | issue = 2| pages = 1\u20135 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book|author1=M.B. Jones|author2=J.M.N. Azevedo|author3=A.I. Neto |author4=Ana Cristina Costa |author5=A.M. Frias Martins |title=Island, Ocean and Deep-Sea Biology: Proceedings of the 34th European Marine Biology Symposium, held in Ponta Delgada (Azores), Portugal, 13\u201317 September 1999|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZdH3CAAAQBAJ&pg=PA192|date=11 November 2013|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=978-94-017-1982-7|pages=192\u2013}}\n*{{cite journal|last1=Montenegro|first1=Javier|last2=Sinniger|first2=Frederic|last3=Reimer|first3=James Davis|title=Unexpected diversity and new species in the sponge-Parazoanthidae association in southern Japan|journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution|volume=89|year=2015|pages=73\u201390|issn=1055-7903|doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2015.04.002|pmid=25863336}}\n*{{cite journal|last1=Ryland|first1=J. S.|last2=Lancaster|first2=J. E.|title=A review of zoanthid nematocyst types and their population structure|journal=Hydrobiologia|volume=530\u2013531|issue=1\u20133|year=2004|pages=179\u2013187|issn=0018-8158|doi=10.1007/s10750-004-2685-1}}\n*{{cite journal|last1=Ryland|first1=John S.|last2=Lancaster|first2=John E.|title=Revision of methods for separating species of Protopalythoa (Hexacorallia : Zoanthidea) in the tropical West Pacific|journal=Invertebrate Systematics|volume=17|issue=3|year=2003|pages=407|issn=1445-5226|doi=10.1071/IS02008}}\n*{{cite journal|last1=Ryland|first1=John S.|last2=Brasseur|first2=Muriel M.|last3=Lancaster|first3=John E.|title=Use of cnidae in taxonomy: implications from a study ofAcrozoanthus australiae(Hexacorallia, Zoanthidea)|journal=Journal of Natural History|volume=38|issue=10|year=2004|pages=1193\u20131223|issn=0022-2933|doi=10.1080/0022293031000155179}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{EOL|43560914|Brachycnemina}}\n*[http://www.marinespecies.org/aphia.php?p=taxdetails&id=367224 WORMS entry]\n\n{{Commons category|Zoantharia}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q20020299}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brachycnemina}}\n[[Category:Zoantharia]]\n[[Category:Cnidarian suborders]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Suborder of cnidarians}}\n{{Automatic taxobox\n| image = Zoanthus sp act\u00ednica.jpg\n| image_caption = ''[[Zoanthus]]'' colony\n| taxon = Brachycnemina\n| authority = Haddon & Shackleton, 1891\n| subdivision_ranks = Families\n| subdivision = * [[Neozoanthidae]] <small>Herberts, 1972</small><br/>\n* [[Sphenopidae]] <small>Hertwig, 1882</small>\n* [[Zoanthidae]] <small>Rafinesque, 1815</small>\n}}\n\n'''Brachycnemina''' is a [[suborder]] of zoanthids in the order [[Zoantharia]].<ref name=\"SinnigerMontoya-Burgos2005\" /> Genetic analysis has been used to suggest Brachycnemina is a [[monophyletic]] group [[Genetic divergence|diverging]] within the [[paraphyletic]] [[Macrocnemina]].<ref name=\"SinnigerMontoya-Burgos2005\">{{cite journal|last1=Sinniger|first1=F.|last2=Montoya-Burgos|first2=J. I.|last3=Chevaldonn\u00e9|first3=P.|last4=Pawlowski|first4=J.|title=Phylogeny of the order Zoantharia (Anthozoa, Hexacorallia) based on the mitochondrial ribosomal genes|journal=Marine Biology|volume=147|issue=5|year=2005|pages=1121\u20131128|issn=0025-3162|doi=10.1007/s00227-005-0016-3|url=http://doc.rero.ch/record/315399/files/227_2005_Article_16.pdf}}</ref>\n\n==Characteristics==\nBrachycnemia species habitate most environments, ranging from shallow tropical [[reef]]s to [[cold seep]]s in the deep sea. It forms large colonies on [[intertidal]] and shallow [[Fringing reef|reef crest]]s.<ref name=\"Gujarat\" /> Due to the members of this suborder being loosely collected, there are no standard characteristics uniting them besides slight [[Morphology (biology)|morphological]], [[ecology|ecological]] and [[phylogenetic]] differences.<ref name=\"REIMER2010\">{{cite journal|last1=REIMER|first1=James Davis|title=Key to field identification of shallow water brachycnemic zoanthids (Order Zoantharia: Suborder Brachycnemina) present in Okinawa|journal=Galaxea, Journal of Coral Reef Studies|volume=12|issue=1|year=2010|pages=23\u201329|issn=1883-3969|doi=10.3755/galaxea.12.23}}</ref>\n\n==Subdivisions==\nThis suborder counts with 3 taxonomic families, namely [[Neozoanthidae]], which is [[monogeneric]]; [[Sphenopidae]], which includes sand-encrusted and colonial specimens like the commonly found ''[[Palythoa]]'' and ''[[Sphenopus]]'', itself found in a few discrete areas; and [[Zoanthidae]], whose belonging species do not show sand encrustation.<ref name=\"Gujarat\" /> A total of 6 known genera and over 163 species are comprised within the Brachycnemina.<ref name=GBIF.org>{{cite web|title=Brachycnemina Haddon & Shackleton, 1891|url=https://www.gbif.org/species/109752249|website=GBIF.org|publisher=GBIF.org|accessdate=21 May 2015|deadurl=yes}}</ref> ''Palythoa'' and ''Zoanthus'' are two of the most common coral genera and are intensively studied for their [[Bioactive compound|bioactive]] compounds.<ref name=\"Gujarat\">{{cite journal | last1 = Pandya Khushali | first1 = M. |display-authors=et al | year = 2014 | title = Occurrence of Zoanthid genus Isaurus from Saurashtra coast, Gujarat, India | url = | journal = European Journal of Zoological Research | volume = 3 | issue = 2| pages = 1\u20135 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book|author1=M.B. Jones|author2=J.M.N. Azevedo|author3=A.I. Neto |author4=Ana Cristina Costa |author5=A.M. Frias Martins |title=Island, Ocean and Deep-Sea Biology: Proceedings of the 34th European Marine Biology Symposium, held in Ponta Delgada (Azores), Portugal, 13\u201317 September 1999|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZdH3CAAAQBAJ&pg=PA192|date=11 November 2013|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=978-94-017-1982-7|pages=192\u2013}}\n*{{cite journal|last1=Montenegro|first1=Javier|last2=Sinniger|first2=Frederic|last3=Reimer|first3=James Davis|title=Unexpected diversity and new species in the sponge-Parazoanthidae association in southern Japan|journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution|volume=89|year=2015|pages=73\u201390|issn=1055-7903|doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2015.04.002|pmid=25863336}}\n*{{cite journal|last1=Ryland|first1=J. S.|last2=Lancaster|first2=J. E.|title=A review of zoanthid nematocyst types and their population structure|journal=Hydrobiologia|volume=530\u2013531|issue=1\u20133|year=2004|pages=179\u2013187|issn=0018-8158|doi=10.1007/s10750-004-2685-1}}\n*{{cite journal|last1=Ryland|first1=John S.|last2=Lancaster|first2=John E.|title=Revision of methods for separating species of Protopalythoa (Hexacorallia : Zoanthidea) in the tropical West Pacific|journal=Invertebrate Systematics|volume=17|issue=3|year=2003|pages=407|issn=1445-5226|doi=10.1071/IS02008}}\n*{{cite journal|last1=Ryland|first1=John S.|last2=B